  <Navbar />
  <main class="post-main">
    <article class="post-article">
      <div class="post-container">
        <header class="post-header animate-on-scroll">
          <div class="breadcrumb">
            <a href="/">← Back to Problems</a>
          </div>
          <div class="problem-meta">
            <span class="problem-number">1</span>
            <span class="difficulty-badge difficulty-easy">Easy</span>
            <div class="leetcode-link">
              <a href="https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path d="M13.483 0a1.374 1.374 0 0 0-.961.438L7.116 6.226l-3.854 4.126a5.266 5.266 0 0 0-1.209 2.104 5.35 5.35 0 0 0-.125.513 5.527 5.527 0 0 0 .062 2.362 5.83 5.83 0 0 0 .349 1.017 5.938 5.938 0 0 0 1.271 1.818c.51.515 1.043.944 1.654 1.207a5.021 5.021 0 0 0 2.004.388 5.086 5.086 0 0 0 2.013-.403 5.484 5.484 0 0 0 1.702-1.211L11.7 16.4l7.312-7.312c.196-.196.4-.4.62-.606.203-.21.35-.467.349-.738.015-.282-.074-.558-.238-.792a1.348 1.348 0 0 0-.307-.418c-.37-.365-.936-.609-1.512-.609-.576 0-1.141.244-1.512.609L12.6 10.345 8.344 6.088a.915.915 0 0 1-.013-1.292.914.914 0 0 1 1.292-.013l4.012 4.013a.914.914 0 0 1 .013 1.292.915.915 0 0 1-1.292.013L8.344 6.088Z" fill="#FFA116"/>
                </svg>
                View on LeetCode
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>
          <h1 class="post-title">Two Sum</h1>
          <p class="post-description">
            Given an array of integers and a target sum, find two numbers that add up to the target and return their indices.
          </p>
          <div class="post-tags">
            <span class="tag">Array</span>
            <span class="tag">Hash Table</span>
            <span class="tag">Two Pointers</span>
          </div>
        </header>

        <section class="post-content">
          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Problem Statement</h2>
            <div class="problem-box glass">
              <p>
                Given an array of integers <code>nums</code> and an integer <code>target</code>, 
                return <em>indices</em> of the two numbers such that they add up to <code>target</code>.
              </p>
              <p>
                You may assume that each input would have <strong>exactly one solution</strong>, 
                and you may not use the same element twice.
              </p>
              <p>You can return the answer in any order.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Examples</h2>
            <div class="example-box glass">
              <h3>Example 1:</h3>
              <pre><code><span class="keyword">Input:</span> nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9
<span class="keyword">Output:</span> [0,1]
<span class="keyword">Explanation:</span> Because nums[0] + nums[1] == 9, we return [0, 1].</code></pre>
            </div>
            
            <div class="example-box glass">
              <h3>Example 2:</h3>
              <pre><code><span class="keyword">Input:</span> nums = [3,2,4], target = 6
<span class="keyword">Output:</span> [1,2]</code></pre>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Approach 1: Brute Force</h2>
            <p>
              The brute force approach is to check every possible pair of numbers to see if they add up to the target.
            </p>
            
            <div class="complexity-analysis glass">
              <h3>Complexity Analysis</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Time Complexity:</strong> O(n²) - We check every pair</li>
                <li><strong>Space Complexity:</strong> O(1) - Only using constant extra space</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <details class="code-section">
              <summary class="code-header">
                <span>Show Brute Force Solution</span>
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="code-content glass">
                <pre><code class="language-python"><span class="keyword">def</span> <span class="function">twoSum</span>(nums, target):
    <span class="keyword">for</span> i <span class="keyword">in</span> <span class="builtin">range</span>(<span class="builtin">len</span>(nums)):
        <span class="keyword">for</span> j <span class="keyword">in</span> <span class="builtin">range</span>(i + <span class="number">1</span>, <span class="builtin">len</span>(nums)):
            <span class="keyword">if</span> nums[i] + nums[j] == target:
                <span class="keyword">return</span> [i, j]
    <span class="keyword">return</span> []</code></pre>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Approach 2: Hash Map (Optimal)</h2>
            <p>
              We can solve this in one pass using a hash map. For each element, we check if its complement 
              (target - current element) exists in the hash map.
            </p>
            
            <div class="algorithm-steps glass">
              <h3>Algorithm Steps:</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Create an empty hash map to store number → index mapping</li>
                <li>Iterate through the array once</li>
                <li>For each element, calculate complement = target - current element</li>
                <li>If complement exists in hash map, return [complement_index, current_index]</li>
                <li>Otherwise, add current element and its index to hash map</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="complexity-analysis glass">
              <h3>Complexity Analysis</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Time Complexity:</strong> O(n) - Single pass through array</li>
                <li><strong>Space Complexity:</strong> O(n) - Hash map can store up to n elements</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <details class="code-section" open>
              <summary class="code-header">
                <span>Optimal Hash Map Solution</span>
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="code-content glass">
                <pre><code class="language-python"><span class="keyword">def</span> <span class="function">twoSum</span>(nums, target):
    <span class="comment"># Hash map to store number -> index mapping</span>
    num_map = {}
    
    <span class="keyword">for</span> i, num <span class="keyword">in</span> <span class="builtin">enumerate</span>(nums):
        complement = target - num
        
        <span class="comment"># Check if complement exists in map</span>
        <span class="keyword">if</span> complement <span class="keyword">in</span> num_map:
            <span class="keyword">return</span> [num_map[complement], i]
        
        <span class="comment"># Add current number and index to map</span>
        num_map[num] = i
    
    <span class="keyword">return</span> []  <span class="comment"># No solution found</span></code></pre>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Visual Explanation</h2>
            <div class="visual-explanation glass">
              <p>Let's trace through the optimal solution with <code>nums = [2,7,11,15]</code> and <code>target = 9</code>:</p>
              
              <div class="trace-steps">
                <div class="trace-step">
                  <strong>Step 1:</strong> i=0, num=2, complement=7, map={} → Add 2: map={2:0}
                </div>
                <div class="trace-step">
                  <strong>Step 2:</strong> i=1, num=7, complement=2, map={2:0} → Found 2! Return [0,1]
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Key Insights</h2>
            <div class="insights-box glass">
              <ul>
                <li>Hash maps provide O(1) average lookup time, making them perfect for complement searches</li>
                <li>We only need one pass through the array, significantly improving efficiency</li>
                <li>By storing indices in the hash map, we can easily return the required indices</li>
                <li>This pattern (using hash maps for complement searches) appears in many other problems</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section animate-on-scroll">
            <h2>Follow-up Questions</h2>
            <div class="followup-box glass">
              <ol>
                <li>What if the array is sorted? Could we use a different approach?</li>
                <li>How would you modify this to find all pairs that sum to the target?</li>
                <li>What if we needed to find three numbers that sum to target (3Sum problem)?</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <footer class="post-footer animate-on-scroll">
          <div class="navigation-links">
            <a href="/" class="nav-link">← All Problems</a>
            <a href="/posts/add-two-numbers" class="nav-link">Next Problem →</a>
          </div>
        </footer>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>

